@node Introduction "Introduction to ClipHandler"

  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

      One day I was preparing distribution archive for one of my other
  packages. When creating list of included files I found that it is very
  hard to copy data from Shell to my text editor. I had to redirect output
  of @{i}Dir @{ui}command to some file, then include that file in editor, then
  delete it. Lot of work!
      Then I had an idea: why not use Clipboard for that kind of job? It
  makes it easier to transfer data: no temporary files, no choosing them in
  text editor - just @{i}Dir @{ui}in Shell and @{i}Paste @{ui}in editor. And so the
  @{"ClipHandler" link AutoDocs/clip-handler.doc/main} was born.
      @{"ClipHandler" link AutoDocs/clip-handler.doc/main} is a DOS handler. After mounting it you can copy data
  to/from handler like with any other DOS device. The handler uses
  @{i}iffparse.library @{ui}and therefore is very small.
@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements for ClipHandler"

  @{b}@{u}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

      @{"ClipHandler" link AutoDocs/clip-handler.doc/main} requires AmigaDOS 2.04 or higher (@{i}iffparse.library @{ui}V37+).
  Automatic installation works only for AmigaDOS 2.1 or higher - if you have
  only AmigaDOS 2.04, you will have to edit @{i}MountList @{ui}yourself.
      Properly set up Clipboard is also required.
@endnode

@node Installation "Installation of ClipHandler"

  @{b}@{u}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

      Use supplied @{i}Installer @{ui}script to copy necessary files. Mount handler
  by double-clicking on it's icon or use @{i}Mount @{ui}command from Shell.
@endnode

@node History "ClipHandler History"

  @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}

      @{b}Version 1.0 (29.3.95)@{ub} - initial release

      @{b}Version 1.1 (9.7.95)@{ub}

    Bug fixes:
    À Handler now unloads its code on exit.

      @{b}Version 1.2 (14.11.95)@{ub}

    Bug fixes:
    À I forgot to open dos.library explicite, which caused SAS/C auto-init
      feature to be used, thus increasing size by more that 800 bytes.
@endnode

@node ToDo "To do in ClipHandler"
@next ToDo

  @{b}@{u}To do@{uu}@{ub}

